<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Network Rail response:</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail (SLC 007)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Level crossings are one of the major risks of a catastrophic derailment, and would not be countenanced if the railway were being built new today. Network Rail has transformed its approach to level crossings in the current control period, reducing risk by 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">5% since 2009 and meeting our target a year early. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To keep improving safety and reducing risk, we would like to see improved co-operation with local authorities to help us close crossings, stronger and more consistent penalties for driving offences at le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">vel crossings, and most importantly, support from government for our ambition for the next control period. </span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6,500 level crossings on our network. These vary considerably from busy public crossings on major ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to remote crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in lightly populated areas to the very large number of private </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and user-worked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our top priority is to get everyone home safe, every day. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the start of CP4 (2009-14) Network Rail transformed its approach to level crossings to meet its target</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of reducing risk by 25%. We now have a much more robust system in place which is producing substantial safety improvements. Changing how we manage level crossings has been the single most important factor in this improvement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Level crossings are safe whe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n used properly, but represent a particularly serious risk of catastrophic derailment if a train hits a road vehicle at speed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The accident at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ufton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nervet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2004 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highlights </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the danger. A vehicle was parked on the crossing in a suicide bid, resulting in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as impact sufficient to derail the train. Five passengers and the driver of the train died as a result, as well as the occupant of the vehicle.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As well as the risk to trains of derailment, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pedestrians are at potential risk should they misuse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Many level crossings are foot crossings rather than road crossings. In the three years to 2012/13, there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ten incidents of trains striking pedestrians compared to 25 of trains striking vehicles. The number of near misses shows the opposite pattern,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with 259 near misses in 2012/13 compared to 95 with vehicles. The pattern is similar for previous years. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Public behaviour at level crossings accounts for around one third (37% for 2012/13 Q4) of the risk on the Train Accident Precursor Indicator Model, and is the category with the highest risk. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Level crossings also represent a potential point of access to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he railway for trespassers, cable thieves, vandals, or people intent on committing suicide. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would not contemplate allowing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">today if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">building the railway again. We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consequently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">believe </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">closing crossings and diverting rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of way </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the best solution, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">face obstacles in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seeking to close crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our submission to government in the Initial Industry Plan for CP5 (2014-19) proposed a further reduction of 25% (of 2009 risk, so a total reduction of 50%). In t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he government’s H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">igh </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">utput </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pecification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tatement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vailable for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a budget of £65 million was allocated. Based on this funding decision, our Strategic Business Plan set a reduced 8% risk reduction as a key outcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">response to the ORR’s draft determinations we have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> restor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the 25% ambition for CP5, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but revised down our estimate of the cost based on the successes of CP4 and what we have learned from them. We have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> made the case for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a total of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£120 million to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> achieve this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over CP5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The value for money this represents is substantially greater as a result.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Other than funding, the main measures that would help us reduce risk further are improved powers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over rights of way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and co-operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o close crossings and proportionate sentencing for misuse of crossings. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to the safety benefits of closing level crossings, there is a performance benefit to the railway. Closing level crossings helps us to meet our ambitions to increase capac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity, run more trains and increase the speed of many parts of the network. There is also a business benefit of lower maintenance costs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Closing crossings can also be of benefit to road users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where a suitable alternative is available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, by reducing congestio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n and waiting times</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We appreciate that level crossings have an impact on road users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and, while we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> minimise the time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">barriers are down as far as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safely possible, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will never compromise safety for convenience. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some level crossings are also not s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uitable for users with disabilities that inhibit mobility, and pedestrians with sensory disabilities can be particularly vulnerable to missing warning lights or sounds. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">closure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of crossings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is not possible, improvements can be made to crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that are not as we would like them to be.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This may be better signage, installing barriers on crossings without them or other physical improvements. We are also working on technology solutions such as GPS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> seismic instruments to improve information avai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lable at crossings about whether a train is coming.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Are current safety measures at level crossings adequate? How should they be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Not all crossings are as we would like them, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in recent years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we have made very substantial improvements. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is is illustrated by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sharp reduction in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulatory e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nforcement notices from the ORR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> regarding level crossings, from around four per year to now being a very rare occurrence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ince the start of CP4 in 2009</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Network Rail has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> changed its management of le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vel crossings beyond recognition, with investment producing very significant improvements. By creating a central team to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">drive improvement management of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by working with our operational route teams</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we have been able to substantially improve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> our knowledge of them, our relationships with the relevant users and other stakeholders and our approach to improving them. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We employ 104 level crossing managers, who each cover a group of crossings in a geographical area. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The managers work with a range</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of stakeholders including local authorities, users of crossings and the community as well as with colleagues in Network Rail. As well as engaging with users, they assess crossings on a standardised method, enabling a judgement to be made as to which cross</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ings need to be improved or closed. This new approach has led to us having much better information both about the physical state of our crossings but also about how users of crossings behave and think. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since 2009 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">closed 700 crossings and made imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rovements to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of £130 million we have red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uced risk by 25.2% on the RSSB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> model, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">meeting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our CP4 target a year early. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">investment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will pay itself back as we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">no longer face</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the costs associated with managing crossings that have been closed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One particular type of crossing, the Automatic Open Crossing – locally controlled (AOCL) has seen a risk reduction of 90% by adding barrier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where previously there was only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">warning equi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">In addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replace or improve safety at level crossings? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Each crossing differs, and therefore different measures are appropriate. Often closing crossings is t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he most appropriate response, and where this is the case a bridge or underpass may be an appropriate replacement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In recent years we have managed to reduce the average cost of foot bridges from over £1 million to £564,000. This varies depending on location</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, land cost and other factors, but is often a good solution. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In some cases there is a suitable alternative crossing a short distance away meaning that we can close one </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">without impeding access.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">680 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings within 200m o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f an alternative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossing, which are particularly good options for closure.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This is especially the case with private crossings, for example where a farmer has two crossings between adjacent fields. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of improving crossings, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is a range of tec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hnologies available and in development. Some lightly-used foot crossings, and many private crossings, simply have signs warning people to stop, look and listen, and we are developing improved ways of warning people about a train’s location. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These use eithe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r GPS, seismic sensors or other detection equipment to improve the information available to users. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Beyond technology, physical improvements or upgrades, actively engaging with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is highly cost-effective, especially for private crossings where there are a small number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">known</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> users. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How should expenditure on improving safety at level crossings be prioritised in relation to other demands on the rail budget? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The £130 million expenditure in CP4 was decided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the same process as an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y othe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r bid for a large budget, through normal internal procedures and the Periodic Review process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We see this expenditure as cost neutral given the saving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from not needing to in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">spect or manage closed crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. As a result</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the business case is strong. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Within the level crossings budget, level crossings are prioritised by the risk they pose and the benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-to-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cost ratio of improving them. These are identified through the use of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wo risk models – the Precursor Indicator Model, which assesses incidents that often precede problems at level crossings, and the RSSB’s Safety Risk Model. This identification is followed by an in-depth assessment by a level crossing manager to fully unders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tand the risks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Finally, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a cost-benefit analysis is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undertaken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to allow us to prioritise those crossings where we can deliver the greatest safety improvement per pound spent. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is not an automatic or insensitive process done remotely by an algorithm but a thoughtful process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based on a site-specific view of risk.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This information is now available on Network Rail’s transparency portal (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">4. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Is Network Rail giving sufficient priority to improving safety at level crossings? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since 2009 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improving safety at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossings ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> been one of our biggest successes in terms of reducing risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, with 25.2% reduction in four years on the RSSB’s model. This reflects the priority and funding level crossings have received in CP4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> how we manage level crossings is now well-embedded into how we operate and maintain the railway. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For CP5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our safety goal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as published in our Strategic Business Plan,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to eliminate fa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">talities and major incidents. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ambitious proposal in our I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nitial Industry Plan to build on the success of CP4 and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduce risk at level crossings by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a further</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 25% was revised down to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 8% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">following the funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">allocation of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> £75 million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the Government’s High Level Output Statement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In our response to the Draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etermination issued by ORR, we have made the case for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> total of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> £120 million to achieve the 25% redu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ction we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">originally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have admitted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shortcomings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in our approach to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> managing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> level crossings in the pas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t and to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">failings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">after incidents. This has led to a strong </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">corporate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">focus on level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, with sufficient </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">credibility for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Tina Hughes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to agree to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our Level Crossings Champion.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tina’s daughter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Olivia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bazlinton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> died</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">along </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with Charlotte Thompson</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a tragic accident in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Elsenham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2005</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e pleaded guilty t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o health and safety charges, and were fined £1 million.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his accide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">had a profound impact on the company and its employees and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has led to the tight focus on level crossing safety we have today. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">5. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Is Government policy and regulatory action by the Office of Rail Regulation (ORR) in relation to safety at level cros</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">sings adequate? What more should the Government and ORR do? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government policy is appropriate as far as directly managing the railway is concerned. There are some issues with planning where we would like to see greater consultation and powers where new housing or development near a level crossing is likely to increa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se traffic and therefore change the risk profile. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Updating or clarifying the law on rights of way, our powers to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> close</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossings and co-operation with highway authorities and local authorities would be very welcome.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One area that would be helpful would be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> greater clarity regarding our understanding of “reasonable practicability” in deciding whether or not we have fulfilled our duties. This is an issue when we have a system to select crossings for improvement or closure, with the inevitable consequence that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> others are not chosen. Agreement with the ORR on how to proceed would be useful for us, especially when accidents happen at crossings we have not selected for improvement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">6. How should the legislation governing level crossings be updated? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l has been closely involved with the Law Commission’s work on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level crossings.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eagerly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">awaiting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">publication</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Commission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Important areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we would welcome change include closure and rights of way, co-operation with local a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthorities and enforcement and sentencing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of driving offences at level crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Closure and rights of way</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Often closing a level crossing is the best solution, especially where there are alternative crossings nearby. There are 680 crossings with an alternative within 200m, meaning that closure should not be unduly inconvenient. However, the process of closing c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rossings can be very slow and bureaucratic.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to formally have the right to seek closure or diversion of rights of way. The legislation governing this is spread across several Acts of Parliament, and would benefit from being contained in a single statute. Similarly, we would welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ability, and resources, to more easily fund closures, including alterations to the highway. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Co-operation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Road Safety Act (2006) does require co-operation between highway authorities and the railway </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is no clear delineation of funding. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any highway authorities, level crossings are not as high a risk as they are for the railway, and many would prefer to focus on other road dangers as higher priorities for them.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lack of co-operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is particularly relevant where crossings need to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> closed and diverted, since Network Rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is not funded to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pay for road improvements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but highway authorities will often prefer to spend money on improvements in alternative locations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another key area for co-operation is in regard to town planning. New de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">velopments near a level crossing, such as a new housing development, can substantially increase the traffic at a crossing, and therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk. Suitable use of S106 agreements can mitigate this, but the system is cumbersome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and local authorities often d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o not think of the impact on level crossings when negotiating S106 agreements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It should be obligatory for developers to pay for the increased mitigation required as a result of their development at level crossings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Enforcement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a major issue for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> us with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nforcement of the law and sentencing of offences in cases of careless and dangerous driving at level crossings. The punishments for driving through a red light, or around barriers, are often wholly inadequate when compared to the potential conseq</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uences. The accident at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ufton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nervet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> demonstrates that rail staff and passengers can lose their lives due to misuse of crossings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, although in that case it was due to suicide rather than careless or reckless driving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Sentencing guidelines should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e changed to reflect the risk of a catastrophic derailment from misuse of level crossings. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Linked to enforcement, authorised users of private crossings should be subject to more exacting requirements, such as extra testing for those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">driving farm vehicles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, or requirements to train employees in how to use the crossing. We would also welcome fixed penalty notices for misuse, and clarification of the law around the establishment of rights of way. The authorised user model is not ideal for some private crossin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gs which are heavily used, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">form could be appropriate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">7. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How should public awareness of safety at level crossings be improved? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail runs a substantial campaign on level crossings across the media to improve and refresh public awareness. We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> run two annual campaigns on television and digital, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> produce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> targeted materials for high-risk groups, in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> particular school children.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A good example of this is our campaign with the rapper Professor Green, urging people not to use headphones at level cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ossings. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also run awareness days at level crossings, where our safety and community staff will talk to drivers while the barriers are down. Often, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BTP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Automated Number Plate Recognition van</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, funded by Network Rail,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will be there. These level crossings are typically selected because they see above average misuse or other problems that need tackling. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Key groups we focus on include those with high risk, such as young drivers, or those who use crossings frequently, su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ch as ramblers and farmers. These groups are targeted through media, such as driving magazines, or at events or group meetings. For user-worked crossings we engage directly with the authorised users of the crossing. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our campaign for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 18s is called R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ail Life</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which includes important safety messages about level crossings among other safety issues. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Level crossings are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an anachronism that we would not consider building into the railway today. In CP4 we have made good progress in reducing risk from level crossings to passengers, railway staff and crossing users, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by over 25% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but there is further to go. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are committed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to achieving a further 25% reduction in risk in CP5, subject to agreeing funding with the ORR. Recognising that we cannot eliminate risk across all 6500 level crossings, we believe it is important we are regulated on a programme of risk reduction. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fficult t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o see how we could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduce risk to as low as reasonably practicable (ALARP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at every crossing at every moment in time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, particularly given the level of misuse of crossings. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However we believe we should achieve ALARP at the portfolio level.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> welcome changes to the law to enable us to more easily close </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crossings. As well as legal changes, greater co-operation between the railway and highway authorities would improve this process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We want to build on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">progress made in CP4,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and hope that our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> improved value for money proposal can be accepted in the last stages of the periodic review process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>